'''Thomas M. "Tom" Devine''' (born June 21, 1951) is a lawyer, lobbyist, and advocate for [[whistleblower]] rights. Devine is the legal director at the non-profit [[Government Accountability Project]], in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name="whistleblower">{{cite web|url=http://whistleblower.org/about/gap-staff/94-tom-devine-legal-director|title=Tom Devine, Legal Director|publisher=whistleblower.org|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> Devine joined [[Government Accountability Project|GAP]] in 1978 as a second-year law student at [[Antioch School of Law]], and became its legal director in 1979.<ref>{{cite web| last=Nusbaum | first=Marci Alboher | title=DEVINE INTERVENTION | date=November–December 2002 | publisher=''[[Legal Affairs]]'' | url=http://www.legalaffairs.org/issues/November-December-2002/story_nusbaun_novdec2002.msp | accessdate=2012-07-04}}</ref> According to his bio, Devine has assisted more than 5,000 whistleblowers and has helped enact or defend more than 20 major whistleblower laws in the United States and abroad.<ref name="whistleblower"/> Currently, Devine is involved with passing the [[Whistleblower Protection Act#Whistleblower Protection Enhancement Act|Whistleblower Protection Enhancement Act of 2012]] through the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]].<ref>{{cite web| last=Davidson | first=Joe | title=Senate passes whistleblower protections — again | date=May 9, 2012 | publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/senate-passes-whistleblower-protections--again/2012/05/09/gIQAL7b4DU_story.html | accessdate=2012-07-05}}</ref>
==Early history== Devine was raised in a working-class family in Elmwood Park, Ill.<ref name="whistleblower"/> His late father was an inspector for a phone company.<ref name="whistleblower"/> Devine participated in the debate team in high school and later became the debate team captain in Georgetown University.<ref name="Washington Monthly">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1316/is_n1_v22/ai_8528241/ "GAP's in your defense - Government Accountability Project."] ''Washington Monthly.'' February 1990.</ref> He enrolled in Antioch Law School in 1977.<ref name="whistleblower"/>
